In .NET MAUI Shell, override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use the `BackButtonBehavior` Shell attached property:

**EditProductPage.xaml**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**EditProductPage.xaml.cs**
```csharp
// Intercepts the hardware/software back button (Android, etc.)
protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
{
    if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // allow normal navigation

    // Show dialog on the main thread (fire-and-forget is fine here
    // because we're blocking navigation synchronously with `return true`)
    Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });

    return true; // cancel the original navigation
}
```

**ViewModel (for the toolbar "Cancel" button)**
```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    if (!HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** — handles the device back button/gesture. Return `true` to cancel navigation.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** — replaces Shell's default back arrow with a "Cancel" label and routes taps through your command instead of the default pop.
- Both paths converge on the same confirm-then-navigate logic; only the entry point differs.

> ⚠️ On iOS, the swipe-back gesture bypasses `OnBackButtonPressed`. Setting `BackButtonBehavior` disables that gesture automatically, so the command path covers iOS.
